
1. docker run
This command creates and starts a container.

Common Flags:

-d: Run the container in detached mode (in the background).
-p: Publish a containerâ€™s port(s) to the host (e.g., -p 8080:80).
--name: Assign a name to the container.
-e: Set environment variables (e.g., -e VAR=value).
-v: Bind mount a volume (e.g., -v /host/path:/container/path).
--rm: Automatically remove the container when it exits.
2. docker ps
This command lists running containers.

Common Flags:

-a: Show all containers (default shows just running).
-q: Only display container IDs.
--format: Format the output using a Go template.
3. docker build
This command builds an image from a Dockerfile.

Common Flags:

-t: Tag the image (e.g., -t myimage:latest).
-f: Specify a Dockerfile (e.g., -f /path/to/Dockerfile).
--no-cache: Build without using cache.
4. docker images
This command lists images on the local machine.

Common Flags:

-q: Only display image IDs.
--filter: Filter output based on conditions (e.g., --filter dangling=true).
5. docker rmi
This command removes one or more images.

Common Flags:

-f: Force removal of the image.
--no-prune: Do not delete untagged parent images.
6. docker exec
This command runs a command in a running container.

Common Flags:

-it: Run the command in interactive mode with a terminal.
-d: Run the command in the background.
7. docker stop
This command stops a running container.

Common Flags:

-t: Set a timeout (in seconds) for the container to stop.
8. docker rm
This command removes one or more stopped containers.

Common Flags:

-f: Force removal of a running container (it will be stopped first).
-v: Remove the volumes associated with the container.
9. docker pull
This command downloads an image from a registry.

Common Flags:

--all-tags: Download all tags of the image.
10. docker push
This command uploads an image to a registry.

Common Flags:

--disable-content-trust: Skip image signing verification.
